{{Judaism}} The Hebrew phrase '''''mitzvah goreret mitzvah, averah goreret averah''''' (Hebrew: מצווה גוררת מצווה; עברה גוררת עברה.) "one good deed will bring another good deed, one transgression will bring another transgression," (''[[Pirkei Avot|Sayings of the Fathers]]'' 4:2) expresses the belief in [[Judaism]] that following one [[mitzvah|commandment]] leads to another.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AJbiDdCkqlIC&pg=PR19&dq=%22Mitzvah+goreret+mitzvah%22&hl=en&ei=X7ASTP-FH8WqlAewmIyICA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Mitzvah%20goreret%20mitzvah%22&f=false |title=Raising a mensch - Shelley Kapnek Rosenberg - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date=2003-06-30 |accessdate=2011-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rME9oA4ixUEC&pg=RA2-PA68&dq=%22Mitzvah+goreret+mitzvah%22&hl=en&ei=X7ASTP-FH8WqlAewmIyICA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22Mitzvah%20goreret%20mitzvah%22&f=false |title=Teaching Jewish Virtues: Sacred ... - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2011-09-20}}</ref> The saying is found in the [[mishnah]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenberg |first=Zushe |url=http://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/519136/jewish/The-Tefillin-That-Helped-Cope-With-Life-and-With-Death.htm |title=The Tefillin That Helped Cope With Life and With Death - Stories |publisher=Chabad.org |date= |accessdate=2011-09-20}}</ref> in ''[[Pirkei Avot]]'' 4:2.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ybB7OMk3nnwC&pg=PA79&dq=%22Mitzvah+goreret+mitzvah%22&hl=en&ei=X7ASTP-FH8WqlAewmIyICA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22Mitzvah%20goreret%20mitzvah%22&f=false |title=Striving toward virtue: a ... - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2011-09-20}}</ref>
There are several ways in which such an effect can take place. One can be as a result of inspiration, in which the act of a mitzvah is witnessed by others, who in turn, follow in their footsteps.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tP-tMShhzlwC&pg=PA51&dq=%22Mitzvah+goreret+mitzvah%22&hl=en&ei=X7ASTP-FH8WqlAewmIyICA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22Mitzvah%20goreret%20mitzvah%22&f=false |title=Succeeding at Jewish education: how ... - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2011-09-20}}</ref> Another is by [[habit (psychology)|habit]], in which a person becomes accustomed to performing a mitzvah regularly.<ref>''Living courageously'' By Samuel Chiel, page 168</ref>
The contrast to this belief is called ''aveira goreret aveira'' in which the commission of an ''[[aveira]]'' (sin) leads to another sin.
The phrase has often been used in songs for children to encourage the performance of good works. One popular song, written by Andy Vogel in 1986, was recorded on the Reform Jewish movement's "NFTY at 50" album,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B003YPF2EW/ref=dm_ws_sp_tlw_trk1?ie=UTF8&qid=1407362167&sr=1-42}}</ref> and is widely sung in the Reform Jewish movement.
==Examples== * A person places money in a pushka ([[tzedaka]] collection box). This is seen by others, who in turn are inspired to place money in the box. * A person helps someone in need, and feels good about themself and therefore continues to do help others.
